    <segment id="1" parent="11" relname="span">I agree completely that intuitiveness is partly learned. </segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="10" relname="span">
By its very nature it demands some sort of frame of reference by the user.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="elaboration"> 
The word indicates that the user will just know what to do. </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="8" relname="nonvolitional-cause">
There has to be something a user can relate to </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="span">
so he/she will &apos;know&apos; what to do. </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="12" relname="span">

To make something intuitive for a novice user it must somehow fit into his frame of reference. </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="elaboration">
There must be something he has learned that relates to the use of the interface. </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="11" relname="evaluation">
That is my opinion.</segment>
